<TITLE> EU concerned over CHT </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 26 (bdnews24.com)  The European Union on Friday expressed deep concern over the recent violence in Chittagong Hill Tracts and called for swift implementation of the peace accord. Catherine Ashton, high representative of EU foreign affairs and security policy, in a statement, also expressed the Union's worries over the reported involvement of armed forces in the incidents in Baghachhari sub district in Rangamati and Khagrachhari district town. The statement said that the EU had received reports that in a number of villages in Rangamati, and notably in Gangarmodor Baghaihat, indigenous people were killed, houses were set on fire and a number of indigenous people were displaced. "The EU strongly condemns the acts of violence that took place in the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) in Bangladesh on 19 and 20 February 2010," the statement read. It said that the EU was 'aware of allegations' that the incident involved army personnel and labourers employed by the army. "The EU calls upon the Government of Bangladesh to swiftly and thoroughly follow up with an independent investigation of this incident and of the allegations that the armed forces were involved." Ashton, in her statement, urged the government to ensure that the perpetrators of these shameful acts are brought to justice. The statement warned that the international reputation of Bangladesh might be harmed if things continued in this directio
